==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

The character represents a pair of knives to butcher animals. The original meaning is preserved in {{och-l|劉}}. An old and conservative variant is {{zh-m|戼}}.

This character was found in oracle bone scripts depicting a sacrifice (a human or animal body) that is cut in half. This kind of practice mainly happened in [[w:Shang dynasty|Shang dynasty]] and was gradually eliminated after [[w:Zhou dynasty|Zhou]]'s conquest of Shang, leading to obscurity of the character's original meaning.

According to Shuowen Jiezi, it is an open door, like {{zh-m|門/𨳇}} but reversed; however, Xu Shen's interpretations are not based on oracle bones and bronzes. Another similar [[folk etymology]] links the character to the [[mortise]] in [[woodworking]].

===Etymology===
Derived from root {{och-l|流|tr=*r(j)u}} with volitional or agentive OC prefix *''m-'' (see {{zh-ref|Sagart, 1999}}); so *''m-ruu''  means "(cause to flow >) pour out, empty" > *''m-ruuʔ'' 卯 "pouring or emptying stage" i.e. "waning moon", "with the word in its sacrificial applications meaning 'to blood-let'" ({{zh-ref|Smith, 2011}}).

Association with the rabbit was probably arbitrary, just as how {{m|zh|辰}} was arbitrarily associated with the dragon (see {{zh-ref|Ferlus, 2013}}).

